These figures are supplied daily as open data by the National Institute for Public Health and the Environment (RIVM): https://data.rivm.nl/covid-19/COVID-19_aantallen_gemeente_cumulatief.json. The file is published online every day at 10.00 and includes the number of hospital admissions in the past 24 hours.  {{whitespace}}

Since 1 May 2020, only admissions were counted where it was not indicated that the admission was due to another reason than Covid-19. This gives a more accurate presentation of how many people are extremely sick due to Covid-19. This number is an as accurate as possible indicator of the epidemic. {{whitespace}}

The source file contains figures per municipality. The national figure is achieved by adding the municipality figures together. Figures are also calculated for each of the safety regions, using the Statistics Netherlands (CBS) allocation of municipalities to safety regions: https://opendata.cbs.nl/#/CBS/nl/dataset/84721NED/table?dl=3A154. {{whitespace}}

At the time of writing, the most recent version of this data set was published on 10 April 2020. This version has been exported and saved as a .JSON file.

The data from the RIVM source file is used to calculate a three-day moving average for COVID-19 hospital admissions up to and including 10.00 on the current day. The moving average is obtained by adding up each day’s figures (up to 10.00 on the current day, and up to 10.00 one day ago and two days ago), dividing the total by three and rounding off the answer to one decimal place.{{whitespace}}

The date under which a case is recorded is the date of notification, as this is more recent than the date of the test that confirmed COVID-19. {{whitespace}} Our aim is to collect early indications of infection, so we use the most recent data and the date of notification. This is not the same as the day on which people were tested. It does, however, lead to an overestimation of the number of hospital admissions. This has been corrected in the historical data that can be found on the RIVM website: https://www.rivm.nl/coronavirus-covid-19/grafieken.

This data is supplied daily as open data by the National Institute for Public Health and the Environment (RIVM): https://data.rivm.nl/covid-19/COVID-19_aantallen_gemeente_cumulatief.json. The file is published online every day at 10.00 and registers the number of postively tested persons in the past 24 hours. {{whitespace}}

The source file contains figures per municipality. Figures are also calculated for each of the safety regions, using the Statistics Netherlands allocation of municipalities to safety regions: https://opendata.cbs.nl/#/CBS/nl/dataset/84721NED/table?dl=3A154. At the time of writing, the most recent version of this data set was from 10 April 2020. This version has been exported and saved as a .JSON file.{{whitespace}}

The increase in the number of daily positive tests is calculated by deducting  the current day’s cumulative number of positive tests reported from the cumulative number reported the day before. This produces the number absolute of daily positive ly tested persons reported, as shown on the dashboard.{{whitespace}}

We also use this number to calculate a relative rate per 100,000 inhabitants. First, we divide the Netherlands’ total population by 100,000. We then divide the number of daily positively tested by the outcome of that division. This gives us the number of daily positive tests per 100,000 inhabitants.{{whitespace}}

The date used is the date of notification. This is not the same as the day on which people were tested. For more information, please go to the RIVM website: https://www.rivm.nl/coronavirus-covid-19/grafieken.
Any corrections to historical data, such as double counting, are processed on the day the error was discovered. This means the number of new cases reported for that day is lower than the actual number, but this is offset by the numbers being too high on previous days. {{whitespace}}

Because of such corrections, it is possible for the current day’s cumulative number to be lower than the number for the day before. This is then depicted as 0 (zero) on the dashboard, as it is impossible to have a negative number of infections. For instance, you cannot have -0.4 infections over the past three days. This is also why discrepancies arise when regional data is aggregated into national data. The national value is the total of all municipalities’ cumulative data for the current day minus the total of all their cumulative data for the day before. It is not the outcome of this same formula using the safety regions’ cumulative data. If the negative values would used for the safety regions, you would get the correct values.{{whitespace}}

The division of new cases by age group is based on the national figures because ages are not recorded in the file containing municipal data. The table on the RIVM website may therefore not always match the table on the dashboard.

Here the number of nursing homes with COVID-19 outbreaks is estimated, by linking the postal codes of residents with COVID-19 with a list of nursing homes. This produces around 15 addresses. The measure is not entirely accurate as precise addresses cannot be used yet. RIVM is working with the municipal health services (GGDs) and Statistics Netherlands (CBS) to develop a more accurate method. The information on the dashboard will be updated as soon as this method is available. {{whitespace}}


Sometimes there seems to be a discrepancy between the new number of nursing homes with infected inhabitants, and the increase in the total amount of infected nursing homes compared to the day before. 

This is due to the fact that by newly infected nursing location, only the number is shown from the previous day. However, new infected nursing homes are not only reported from the day before, but sometimes earlier as well. As a consequence "the number of new locations since yesterday" is not always the same as the increase in total number of infected nursing homes. We are currently working to show this more clearly on the dashboard as soon as possible.

These figures are supplied weekly (on Tuesdays) as open data by the National Institute for Public Health and the Environment (RIVM): https://data.rivm.nl/covid-19/COVID-19_prevalentie.json. The values in the file are copied directly onto the dashboard. We also convert these absolute numbers into a relative rate of infectious people per 100,000 inhabitants. We do this by dividing the Netherlands’ total population by 100,000. We then divide the absolute number of infectious people by the outcome of that division. The resulting figure is the number of infectious people per 100,000 inhabitants.{{whitespace}}

The RIVM bases the  number of infectious people on the daily reports of the number of people with COVID-19. Until 30 June this value was based on the daily number of patients admitted to an ICU with COVID-19. Because the number of people currently being admitted to ICUs with COVID-19 is low, the number of people reported as having COVID-19 is a better indicator to track the progression of the number of infectious people.
RIVM calculates the number of infectious people based on the number of infected people and the duration of the infectious period. The duration of the infectious period differs from one person to another, but is between 6 and 10 days. The number of infected people is based on the number of COVID-19 cases reported.
RIVM uses a conversion factor to take account of people who are infected with coronavirus but who remain unreported. The conversion factor is derived from confirmed COVID-19 hospital admissions and the percentage of people whose blood contains antibodies to the virus that causes COVID-19. RIVM is considerate of the fact that a tiny percentage of the tests could give a false positive result.{{whitespace}}
