A representative sample of around 350 GP practices across the Netherlands provide data once a week to the Netherlands Institute for Health Services Research (NIVEL) Primary Care Database concerning the symptoms of patients they have seen. Using this data, NIVEL determines how many patients who saw their GP in the past week had suspected COVID-19. NIVEL determines this on the basis of the diagnostic codes reported by GPs (‘acute upper respiratory system infection’, ‘other respiratory infection(s)’, ‘influenza’, ‘pneumonia’, ‘other viral disease(s)’, ‘other infectious disease’, ‘fever’, ‘shortness of breath’, ‘coughing’) and any additional information provided that is suggestive of COVID-19. {{whitespace}}

To improve this indicator’s accuracy, NIVEL also recalculates the data for the preceding weeks, so they can include any information that only became available at a later time.
The NIVEL Primary Care Database provides this information once a week (thursdays) and  delives this information in JSON format to the Ministry of Health, Welfare and Sport in. The source file gives the numbers per week. On the dashboard, these are shown as the weekly figures using Sunday’s date. The weekly values in the file are copied directly onto the dashboard.
